exciting regions, the western side of the Arabian 
Sea. And up to this day, no physical oceanography

25:07.172 --> 25:19.189
work of any quality has been done on the Indian 
Shelf, because afterwards the Suez Canal was

25:07.172 --> 25:19.189
closed, and so... Well, as I said, I published in 
the- made a very meritorious publication, I'm

25:20.317 --> 25:33.198
still very proud of, but because it was published 
at the- in the wrong place and perhaps in the wrong-

25:20.317 --> 25:33.198
at the wrong time to- that was it. Had I gone to a 
congress, of course, and had given speeches, it

25:33.399 --> 25:44.677
would have been different, but of course I 
couldn't get from there to New York.

25:44.697 --> 25:46.881
Now, yeah, had I gone to a congress, There was a big 
Congress in 1959, the first international

25:47.114 --> 25:54.438
Congress on Oceanography held in New York, to 
which I couldn't go. But at that Congress, the

25:55.240 --> 25:59.875
Department of Oceanography here in Seattle began 
to look around for a new biologist because their

26:00.260 --> 26:14.483
biological oceanographer had not panned out, had 
not published and had to go after his six years, was

26:00.260 --> 26:14.483
not promoted, and so they wanted to replace him. 
And Ratri, who happens now to be chairman, talked

26:15.364 --> 26:27.904
around and asked, do you know somebody, and ran 
into Krai, and Krai said, sure, I have somebody

26:15.364 --> 26:27.904
who's in India and who might be interested. And so I 
got the advertisement, and would I be interested

26:29.015 --> 26:34.603
to apply? and to cut this story short I did apply 
because in Germany there was still no position and

26:35.647 --> 27:04.388
although I was sort of assured that I wouldn't have 
to starve it was clear that in order to enter the

26:35.647 --> 27:04.388
university career I would still have many many 
years of waiting without lecturing without well

26:35.647 --> 27:04.388
just work on my own and I thought I was not old enough 
to shoulder responsibility and perhaps begin

26:35.647 --> 27:04.388
lecturing and so I wrote to Seattle and said, yes, I 
would like to apply, but since I had burned my

27:05.667 --> 27:25.547
fingers in India so badly, I didn't want to go right 
away, sign my contract while still in India, but

27:05.667 --> 27:25.547
suggested, asked, could I come over and look at the 
situation over, and that suited them eminently

27:05.667 --> 27:25.547
because they, of course, didn't want to buy 
somebody either whom they had never seen. So

27:25.587 --> 27:35.337
immediately after returning from India in spring 
of 1960, I went here for six weeks and liked it very

27:25.587 --> 27:35.337
much. And they liked me too, and so that was it. And I 
appeared on the scene here in autumn of 1960. The

27:43.311 --> 27:48.128
reason why I came here was the unsatisfactory 
situation in Germany. But more importantly, the

27:49.694 --> 28:02.761
positive aspect that the philosophy here, the 
definition of oceanography, which is really due

27:49.694 --> 28:02.761
to Barnes, Fleming, and Barnes and Rattray, was 
very much the one I was used to. It was not marine

28:02.781 --> 28:08.412
biology or biology of marine organisms, but it was 
really oceanography. And they offered me a

28:10.012 --> 28:17.064
position of responsibility and I also could enter 
the teaching career right away. So it was really

28:17.285 --> 28:27.042
more the positive aspect than the fact that in 
Germany I would just have to do research, continue

28:17.285 --> 28:27.042
to do research. But the upshot was that because of 
all the duties piled upon me, the plankton work

28:28.456 --> 28:36.885
from the Indian Ocean was never published. All the 
samples had been counted, all the analysis done,

28:36.986 --> 28:43.433
but I had never had time to publish, which is sad in a 
way. But I had never had the three months or so which

28:43.993 --> 28:50.000
I would have needed to publish. So that is still 
there.

28:55.647 --> 28:57.028
Are you ready to begin the Seattle career? Yes. OK.

